{Having made my first chess steps during Fischer's years of glory I could not
help developing a strong sympathy towards the king's bishop, irrespective of
the color I was playing with. From my early years opening repertoire the
Sozin/Velimirovic/Fischer attack (6.Bc4 in several Sicilian systems) couldn't
miss and I scored many spectacular wins using the strength of my light-squared
bishop. 
Many decades later (more precisely in 1992) I included the Catalan
in my repertoire. Fischer's favorite bishop's influence was once again clear,
but this time the main diagonal was h1-a8. White's main ambitions are
connected with the center and the queenside, something highlighted in the
previous articles. But there are games when after a long introductory fighting
phase on the usual areas White uses his higher mobility (deriving from his
space advantage and light initiative) for suddenly switching to a deadly
kingside attack. This is the subject of the present article. 
In such cases
the Catalan bishop can be a hero in two ways. It can either keep Black busy on
the kingside, or it could join the attack with, say, Be4. 
We will start
with an example where the influence of my early years experience with the
Sozin Attack is obvious.} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. d4 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Be7 6.
Bg2 O-O 7. O-O c6 8. Qc2 b6 9. Rd1 Ba6 10. b3 Nbd7 11. a4 $5 {White tries
proving that Bc1-d2 did not spoil his coordination but can be useful as an
extra tempo.} Rc8 12. a5 c5 13. axb6 Qxb6 14. Qa2 Nb8 15. Ba5 Qd6 16. Nbd2 {
White has some light initiative, but of course, the drawish tendency is
noticeable. The outcome of the game greatly depends on each player's tactical
ability, as minor pieces are likely to become active soon.} cxd4 17. Nxd4 Bd8
18. cxd5 Nxd5 19. Nc4 Qc5 {[#]Facing the danger of massive exchanges, White
needs playing energetically:} 20. Nf5 $1 {Not a difficult move to find, but
its implications are deeper than it may seem at first sight. The focus is put
on d5, but the knight also moves closer to the kingside.} Nb4 ({Relatively
best, as after both} 20... exf5 21. Rxd5 $16) ({and} 20... Bxc4 21. bxc4 Bxa5
22. Qxa5 Qxa5 23. Rxa5 Rxc4 24. Bxd5 $16 {Black is likely to land in an ending
with 3 pawns versus 4 on the same wing. The presence of minor pieces would
offer White more realistic winning chances than in a pure rook ending.}) 21.
Qd2 {Setting the second piece of the attacking puzzle. Attacking the knight
just helps to gain a tempo, but the main idea is re-directing the queen on the
attacking path.} N4c6 22. Bxc6 {By exchanging the bishop at the right time
White challenges Black's stability. Due to the hanging d8-bishop the next move
is forced, but then the other bishop will be left without defense.} Nxc6 {[#]}
23. Bc3 $1 {White keeps his knight on f5, offering its exchange for the
a6-bishop, which would leave him with at least more pleasant play. My opponent
failed to understand that I also completed the attacking puzzle. He thought I
had simply blundered a piece and with a trembling hand played:} Bxc4 $4 {
Obviously hoping for 24.bxc4? Qxf5.} ({He should have just taken my knight,
for instance} 23... exf5 24. Rxa6 Be7 25. Qe3 $14) ({or} 23... Qxf5 24. Nd6 Qg5
25. Rxa6 Qxd2 26. Rxd2 Rc7 $14 {in both cases with chances to defend in a
somewhat passive position.}) {[#]I was surprised that my opponent's alarm
bells did not ring, I briefly checked my intended move again and then played:}
24. Qh6 $1 {Just when Black has solved his queenside problems, he gets mated
on the opposite wing!} 1-0

