{In order to clarify the way my years with the Sozin attack inspired me in the
previous game, I will insert one of my favorite wins from those times:} 1. e4
c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Bc4 e6 7. Bb3 Be7 8. Be3 a6
9. Qe2 Nxd4 10. Bxd4 b5 11. O-O-O O-O 12. g4 Qc7 13. g5 Nd7 14. Qh5 Nc5 15.
Rhg1 {[#]} Nxb3+ $2 {In this game it is Black who (mistakingly) exchanges
White's king's bishop (compare with my Bxc6).} ({The correct continuation is} 
15... Bb7 {when the same attack as in the game does not work out so well, as I
knew from a game played by my first trainer:} 16. Bf6 Rfc8 17. Rg4 b4 18. Rh4
Bxe4 $1 {A first moment when the knight proves useful.} 19. Rxe4 bxc3 20. Rh4
Nxb3+ 21. Kb1 Nd2+ 22. Rxd2 h6 23. Rd1 {In Bordonada-Pavlov, Nice 1974 Black
could have won with} cxb2) 16. axb3 b4 (16... Bb7 {does not work anymore as
White already has} 17. Rd3 $1 {(not available with the knight on c5) when all
the major pieces are ready for the decisive attack.}) 17. Bf6 bxc3 {[#]} 18.
Qh6 $1 {Finally the same pattern as against Kiselef.} 1-0

