{In the next example White started his sudden attack based on his piece
activity, which proved decisive even though there was no pawn tension in the
center.} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 d5 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O Be7 5. d4 O-O 6. c4 dxc4 7. Qc2
a6 8. a4 Bd7 9. Rd1 Bc6 10. Nc3 {[#]An interesting plan. White does not hurry
to retrieve the pawn, but hopes getting an advantage in the center.} Bb4 $6 {
This prevents e2-e4 but moving with the kingside bishop again cannot be a good
idea as long as the queenside is underdeveloped.} ({But the natural} 10... Nbd7
{runs into} 11. e4 {Threatening to win the bishop.} b5 12. d5 exd5 13. e5 $16 {
with overwhelming initiative even though in practice White has frequently gone
wrong in the ensuing complications.}) ({The right way to complete the
development is} 10... Bxf3 $1 11. Bxf3 Nc6 12. Bxc6 bxc6 {White's weaknesses
along the a-file prevent him from fully enjoying the vulnerability of Black's
tripled pawns.}) 11. Bg5 Nbd7 $6 {Another careless move.} ({The lesser evil is
} 11... Bxc3 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. Qxc3 $14 {when Black's position remains
playable.}) {[#]} 12. d5 $1 {This phase of the game could have also landed
into the d4-d5 article.} exd5 13. Nxd5 Bxd5 14. Rxd5 {Black's opening play has
run into a complete fiasco. White has the bishops' pair and will have no problems
retrieving the pawn, while the black bishop is out of play. One would think
that the game would simplify to an ending favoring White, but there are
additional ideas...} Qe7 $2 ({With hindsight} 14... Qe8 {was better. But Black
must have thought that tempting the Catalan bishop releasing the latent
pressure on b7 was a good idea.}) 15. Bh3 $1 {Threatening to win a piece.} Qe8
16. Rd4 {[#]As strange as it may seem, White piece activity already ensures
him a practically decisive advantage.} h6 {Without any constructive plan
available, Black tries forcing matters.} ({The last move allows an immediate
tactical solution, but cannot be criticized too harshly, as after a neutral
move such as} 16... Bd6 {aiming to neutralize the pressure along the d-file
White could play} 17. Rh4 h5 ({If} 17... g6 {the least White can do is winning
an exchange with} 18. Bh6) (17... h6 $6 {is refuted in an even simpler way
than in the game:} 18. Bxh6 gxh6 19. Qc1 $1 {followed by Qxh6.}) 18. Bxd7 {
White will win the h-pawn with a continuing attack.}) 17. Bxd7 $1 {Parting
with the bishop just in time to weaken Blak's kingside defense.} Nxd7 18. Re4 $1
{Another important intermediate move, forcing the queen to go far away from
the king.} Qc8 {[#]} 19. Bxh6 $1 {This does not come as a real surprise as the
king has no defenders with the exception of the pawns.} Nf6 ({If} 19... gxh6 20.
Rg4+ Kh8 21. Qc1 Kh7 22. Rh4 $18 {followed by Qxh6.}) 20. Rxc4 {Winning a pawn
on the way, based on the hanging b4-bishop.} c5 {White is a pawn up and could
switch back to technical play, but Romanishin rightly felt he could finish
things off quicker.} 21. Rf4 Nh7 22. Rh4 {Threatening Bxg7.} gxh6 23. Rxh6 f5
24. Qc4+ Kg7 ({Or if} 24... Rf7 25. Rxh7) 25. Qh4 Rh8 {[#]} 26. Rd1 {Calmly
planning Rdd6. Black has no defense as most of his pieces are isolated on the
opposite wing.} c4 27. Ne5 {Facing the threat Rd7+ Black resigned.} 1-0

