{The kingside attack may also come as a punishment for Black if he prematurely
embarks forced play with material gaining before completing his queenside
development. It is curious that more than one experienced players have fallen
into the following opening trap:} 1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 Be7 5. g3
O-O 6. Bg2 dxc4 7. Ne5 c5 ({The main alternative is} 7... Nc6) 8. dxc5 Qc7 $6 {
Slowly heading for troubles.} 9. Nxc4 Bxc5 10. O-O {[#]} Bxf2+ {The temptation
to win a pwn is strong as Black does not have weaknesses (yet!).} ({Another
unfortunate tactical operation is} 10... Rd8 11. Bf4 Bxf2+ $2 12. Kxf2 $1 {
Preventing ...Rxd1 with a check.} e5 13. Nb5 Qe7 14. Bd2 {and White kept his
material advantage in Portisch-Matanovic, Skopje 1968 (1-0, 38), One important
point is that} Qc5+ {runs into} 15. Be3 {and the back rank weakness dooms
Black.}) 11. Rxf2 Qxc4 12. Rxf6 $1 {The well-deserved punishment. White uses
the f-file to chronically weakening Black's kingside.} gxf6 13. Bh6 {[#]Even
though White needs a few more moves to make his threats real, Black is not in
time bringing his queenside pieces into the defense.} Qc5+ {The queen has some
problems approaching the kingside and now is a good moment preparing it. One
move later it could be too late due to Ne4.} ({If} 13... Nc6 {hoping to return
the exchange and keep the extra pawn White can play} 14. e3 $1 {planning Ne4
without fearing ...Qd4+ but also Qh5.} Rd8 15. Qh5 e5 16. Ne4 Qe6 17. Qh4 {
1-0 Ivkov,B-Robatsch,K Vinkovci 1968}) (13... Re8 14. Ne4 {wins on the spot as
apart from Nxf6+ White also threatens Nd6.}) ({Or if} 13... Nd7 {as in
Psakhis-Stefansson, Winnipeg 1997} 14. Bxf8 Kxf8 15. Qd2 {[%cal Ga1f1,Gd2h6]
with fantastic "Catalan" compensation on both wings. The main plan is Qh6+
followed by Rf1.} Qc5+ 16. Kh1 Qg5 17. Qd6+ Kg7 18. Ne4 $16 {and Black will
most likely never complete his queenside development.}) {[#]} 14. e3 {
Threatening Qg4+} f5 15. Rc1 Qe7 16. Qd4 f6 (16... e5 17. Nd5 $18 {is even
worse.}) 17. Bxf8 Qxf8 18. Nb5 Nc6 {Black has survived the first wave of
attack, but a new one is about to start.} 19. Bxc6 $1 {Clearing the rook's
path to the seventh rank.} bxc6 20. Rxc6 Bb7 21. Rc7 Rd8 22. Qh4 Rd1+ 23. Kf2
Rd2+ 24. Ke1 Rd1+ {The last revenge check.} 25. Kxd1 {I assume Black only now
noticed that the white rook is defended, making 25...Qd8+ ineffective.} 1-0

