{In these games White carried out his attack on dark squares, but also
typically for the Catalan opening this should happen on light squares. Here is
a typical example when the attack started all of a sudden after a long
struggle focusing on White's a5-pawn.} 1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. g3 e6 4. Bg2 Be7
5. O-O O-O 6. c4 dxc4 7. Qc2 a6 8. a4 Nc6 9. Qxc4 Qd5 10. Qd3 Rd8 11. Nc3 Qh5
12. Qc4 Nd5 13. a5 $14 {[#]With his last move White consolidated his space
advantage but my opponent thought he would now have a clear target on a5.} Nxc3
{This strengthens White's center but otherwise Black could not carry out his
intended plan.} 14. bxc3 Bd6 {Defending c7 and threatening ...Nxa5 already.}
15. Ng5 {The maneuver initiated with this move apparently delays the loss of
the a5-pawn only, but the main detail is that Black will have to weaken his
kingside on the way.} h6 16. Bf3 Qg6 17. Ne4 Qf5 18. Qd3 {Defending the pawn
indirectly as 18...Nxa5? 19.Nxd6 wins a piece.} Be7 {Threatening ...Ne5.} 19.
Bg2 Nxa5 $6 {[#]After a series of more or less forced moves Black thought he
achieved his main aim with nothing to worry about.} 20. g4 $1 {Dynamically
this does not molest Black, as he can defend his knight, but the last move is
the first step of the attack.} Qb5 21. c4 $1 {An important intermediate
queenside move forcing Black weakening his kingside defense.} Nxc4 $6 ({
Once again, Black is concerned only about local dynamic factors. His
calculation convinced him he would not lose a piece so he gladly took the
second pawn. ***With hindsight, the best surviving chance was} 21... Qxc4 22.
Rxa5 Qxd3 23. exd3 Rxd4 $14 {when White may experience problems winning with a
knight versus three pawns, partly due to his imperfect structure.}) (21... Qb6
$6 {would not change much with respect to the game, as it would weaken the
control over g5:} 22. g5 (22. Be3 {is also unpleasant.}) 22... Rxd4 (22... hxg5
23. Bxg5 {threatens Rfb1 or simply continuing the attack with a later Ng5.})
23. Qg3 {and so on.}) 22. Rb1 Bb4 {[#]Black's minor pieces are hanging but it
would be a mistake continuing playing on that wing. It is much better to use
the fact that there are no defenders left on the kingside!} 23. g5 $1 {The
weakening induced by ...h7-h6 is now obvious.} ({My opponent had calculated
such variations:} 23. Nc3 Qa5 $1 24. Qxc4 Bxc3 25. Be3 e5 {and White does not
come close to trapping the bishop.}) (23. Bf4 $2 e5 24. Bxe5 Nxe5 25. Qxb5 axb5
26. Rxb4 Nc6 $19 {White not only is a pawn down, but his pawns are hanging
more than Black's.}) (23. Qb3 $2 a5 24. Nc3 Qa6 $19 {and Black keeps his
material advantage.}) 23... h5 (23... hxg5 24. Nxg5 {followed by Qh3 wins
easily.}) {[#]} 24. g6 $1 {Continuing the devastating pawn march.} f6 {
Strategically the most consistent, but offering White the simple plan of
intruding with the queen to h7.} (24... f5 25. Ng5 {is even worse.}) ({Or if} 
24... fxg6 {White has a choice between the thematic} 25. Ng5 {followed by Qxg6
when Black would have to abandon his minor pieces with ...Qf5 now or on the
next move, and 25.Bg5 attacking the rook and threatening Rfc1 also winning a
piece.}) 25. Qh3 {Threatening Rxb4 followed by Qxh5.} a5 {[#]} 26. Nc5 $1 {
Preparing a piece sacrifice in order to open the queen's path to h7.} Rxd4 27.
Qxh5 Qxc5 28. Qh7+ Kf8 29. Bh6 $1 $18 {Not the only winning move, but quite a
thematic one. After having taken over the control on light squares, White now
attacks g7, with the aim of promoting his g-pawn.} Ne5 30. Bxg7+ Ke8 31. Qh8+
Kd7 32. Bxf6 Qf8 33. g7 Qxf6 34. g8=Q Qxh8 35. Qxh8 Bd6 {With insufficient
compensation for the queen and his king under attack, Black resigned without
waiting for my answer.} 1-0

