{[#]White played} 17. a4 {aiming to cause Black some queenside discomfort.
Apart from axb5, a4-a5 may be a positional threat. And if 17...bxa4 18.Nxa4
with some light pressure. Black hoped to solve all these micro-problems with
the counter-attacking} Nd5 {Was this a good idea? Of course not! Black
should not have weakened his kingside defense.} 18. Bxh6 $1 (18. Nxd5 Bxd5 19.
Bxh6 {is equally good.}) 18... gxh6 19. Qxh6 {Threatening Ng5 but also a4-a5
and Rd4.} Nxc3 ({Or if} 19... N5f6 20. Rxd7 Nxd7 21. Ng5 Nf6 22. Bxb7 $1 ({
The correct move order as if} 22. Qxf6 $6 Bxg2 23. Kxg2 Bd4 $1 24. Qh6 f6 {
Black is not without chances due to the hanging c3-knight.}) 22... Qxb7 23.
Qxf6 Bd8 {Far less effective than ...Bd4, of course.} 24. Qh6 Bxg5 25. Qxg5+
Kh7 26. Rd1 $18 {White has two pawns for the exchange and a continuing attack.
Besides, the b5-pawn is hanging in some lines.}) 20. Rxd7 Nxe2+ 21. Kh1 Bxf3
22. Rxa7 Bxg2+ 23. Kxg2 Rxa7 24. Qg5+ Kh7 25. Qh5+ Kg7 26. Qxe2 {And White won.
} bxa4 27. Qe5+ Kg8 28. Qg5+ Kh7 29. Rc1 Rg8 30. Qh5+ Kg7 31. Qe5+ Kh7 32. Rc4
Rg6 33. Rc8 1-0

