{[#]In this theoretical position play usually gravitates around the d4-pawn.
Should White retrieve it without allowing Black completing his development his
chances would be better. But Tal was true to his style with:} 14. Nxf7 $5 Kxf7
15. Ne5+ Nxe5 16. Bxe5 b6 17. Qf3+ Kg8 18. Qg4 g6 19. Be4 {How would you
defend with Black?} Be8 $2 {This natural move, over-defending g6, loses.} ({
It was more important to defend the c-file and the long diagonal with the
paradoxical} 19... Bc6 $1 20. Bxg6 hxg6 21. Qxg6+ Kf8 22. Qh6+ Ke8 23. b4 $1 {
The best way to ensure a draw by perpetual.} Nxb4 24. Qh5+ {The king cannot
escape checks as} Kd7 $2 {allows} 25. Rxc5 $1 bxc5 26. Qf7#) 20. b4 $1 {
Retrieving part of the material and causing Black to lose coordination.} Nxb4
21. Bxa8 Qxa8 22. Qxe6+ Bf7 (22... Kf8 23. Qf6+ Bf7 {transposes.}) 23. Qf6 Kf8
24. Qh8+ Ke7 25. Bf6+ Kd7 26. Bxd8 Nc6 (26... Qxd8 27. Rxd4+ Bxd4 28. Qxd4+ Nd5
29. e4 $18) 27. Bf6 Qxh8 28. Bxh8 {And White converted his material advantage.}
Bxa2 29. e3 a5 30. Bxd4 Nxd4 31. exd4 Bd6 32. d5 a4 33. Rc6 Bc5 34. Rc1 Bd4 35.
R6c4 Bxc4 36. Rxc4 b5 37. Rxd4 a3 38. Rd1 b4 39. Ra1 Kd6 40. Kf1 Kxd5 41. Ke2
1-0

