[White "Line 1 Bogo-Indian Catalan"]
[Black "4...c5"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "E11"]
[Annotator "GM Mihail Marin"]
[PlyCount "39"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 Bb4+ {The Bogo-Indian and the Catalan are closely
related. Even if White plays 3.Nf3, he usually meets the early check with 4.
Bd2 and g2-g3. But with our Catalan move order, we can frequently play more
flexible than in the genuine Bogo-Indian, by delaying the knight's development
or even changing its route.} 4. Bd2 c5 {This is one of the traditional setups.
Black agrees to capture away from the center in order to restrict the b1-knight
and try getting the c5-square for his knights after ...d7-d6 and ...e6-e5.} 5.
Bxb4 cxb4 6. Bg2 O-O ({This is a first moment when the move order counts.
Black has to delay his plan until castling as} 6... d6 $2 {allows} 7. Qa4+ {
winning the b4-pawn as} Nc6 {only makes things worse:} 8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. Qxc6+
Bd7 10. Qxd6 $18) (6... a5 7. a3 {does not change anything essentially.}) 7. a3
$1 {A well-timed break. The point is that Black needs releasing the tension or
else sacrifice a pawn with unclear compensation. Once again this happens
because the long diagonal is open.} (7. e4 d6 8. Ne2 e5 9. O-O Nc6 {leads to
normal positions, with entirely satisfactory stability on dark squares for
Black.}) 7... bxa3 (7... Qc7 8. c5 $14) (7... Qe7 8. Nf3 {and Black cannot
play ...d7-d6 without releasing the tension.}) ({The most ambitious try is} 7...
Nc6 8. Bxc6 {This spoils Black's structure and in certain lines wins a pawn.}
dxc6 (8... bxc6 9. axb4 Qb6 10. Ra4 $14) 9. Nf3 ({Playing for rapid
development and control on dark squares.} 9. axb4 {is also possible:} e5 10.
Nf3 exd4 11. Qxd4 Qe7 12. Qc5 {with just some compensation for Black.}) 9...
bxa3 10. Rxa3 b5 11. O-O a5 12. Nbd2 bxc4 (12... a4 13. b3) (12... Qc7 13. c5
b4 14. Ra1 Ba6 15. Re1 Bb5 16. Ne5 Rfd8 17. e3 Nd7 18. Nxd7 Rxd7 19. b3 Bd3 20.
Nf3 Bb5 21. Ng5 {/\Ne4-d6}) 13. Nxc4 Ba6 (13... c5 14. dxc5 $18) (13... Qc7 14.
Qc2 c5 15. Nce5 $16) 14. Qc2 $16 {White has the better structure and active
position. Black cannot create threats against the enemy king using his bishop.}
) (7... Na6 {has the drawback of blocking the own a-pawn.} 8. Qd2 ({It is
useful insisting with the pressure on b4 before Black gets developed. But} 8.
Nf3 {is also viable:} d6 9. O-O Bd7 10. axb4 Nxb4 11. Nc3 Qc7 12. b3 a5 13. Qd2
b5 {Erdos,V (2581)-Farago,I (2491) Balatonlelle 2009 (½-½, 58)} 14. Rfc1 $5
$14) 8... Qa5 (8... bxa3 9. Nxa3 $14 {with an improved version of the main
line.}) (8... Qb6 9. c5 $16) 9. Nf3 Ne4 ({Black also tries forcing maters.
Slow play helps White:} 9... d6 10. O-O Bd7 11. Ne1 Qb6 12. Nc2 b3 13. Ne3 $16
{White has freed the c3-square for his knight and can enjoy his space
advantage and perfect coordination.}) 10. Qd3 bxa3+ 11. Nfd2 Nxd2 12. Qxd2
Qxd2+ 13. Kxd2 Nc7 (13... axb2 $2 14. Rxa6) 14. Nxa3 $14 {White has more space
and better development while the c7-knight is passive.}) 8. Nxa3 d6 9. Nf3 Nc6
10. O-O e5 (10... a6 11. Nc2 d5 {Ivanov,M (2489)-Berezjuk,S (2436) Czechia
2008 (½-½, 26)} 12. Nd2 $14 {[%cal Gb2b4] followed by b2-b4.}) 11. Nb5 ({
Alternatively,} 11. b4 {is also interesting.} e4 (11... Nxb4 12. dxe5 dxe5 13.
Qxd8 Rxd8 14. Nxe5 Rb8 15. Rfb1 a5 16. c5 Bf5 17. Rc1 Rdc8 18. c6 bxc6 19. Nac4
$14) 12. Nd2 (12. Ng5 Bf5 {left the knight misplaced in Werle,J (2575)-Antic,D
(2523) Rethymno 2009 (½-½, 22)}) 12... e3 (12... Bf5 13. Nc2 $14) 13. fxe3
Nxb4 14. Nc2 (14. Nb5 a5 15. e4 $14) 14... Nxc2 15. Qxc2 Re8 16. e4 a5 17. e3
Ng4 18. Ra3 $14 {With an impressive pawn mass in the centre.}) 11... a6 ({
Undermining White's control on d4 does not work too well either:} 11... Bg4 12.
h3 Bxf3 13. Bxf3 a6 14. dxe5 dxe5 {Nguyen,N (2636)-Liu,Y (2411) Tashkent 2016 
(1-0, 24).} 15. Nd6 $1 $146 Qe7 16. c5 $14 {Now and below it is better to keep
queens as White has more space.}) 12. dxe5 dxe5 13. c5 e4 14. Ng5 Bh3 {
Unpining the a-pawn. Nisipeanu,L (2664)-Iordachescu,V (2607) Eforie Nord 2009 
(1-0, 38)} 15. Nd6 $1 $146 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 Qe7 17. Qc2 e3 18. Ra4 {WHite
suddenly has attacking chaances.} h6 19. Nf5 Qe5 20. Nf3 $16 {followed by Nxe3.
} *

[Event "?"]
