1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Qe7 5. Bg2 (5. Nf3 Nc6 6. Nc3 {would
transpose to the main Bogo-Indian line in this system.}) 5... Nc6 {This is
another traditional setup, planning to adopt a King's Indian structure with ...
d7-d6 and ...e6-e5, after having exchanged the "bad" (but sometimes good or
killing) bishop.} 6. e3 {Once again a typical Catalan setup. Not only
consolidating the d4-pawn and starting a coherent developing plan but also
keeping the e4-square under control. White mainly plays in the spirit of the
following English variation: 1.c4 e5 2.g3 c6 3.d4 Bb4+ 4.Bd2 Bxd2+ 5.Qxd2
followed by e2-e3 and Nge2. The differences here are that Black has wasted a
tempo with his e-pawn and spent another one on the generally useful ...Qe7,
which, however, reduces his chances for early counterplay.} (6. Nf3 Bxd2+ {
forces} 7. Nbxd2 {as else ...Ne4 would be molesting.}) 6... Bxd2+ (6... e5 7.
d5 Bxd2+ ({Black can try maintaining the tension with} 7... Nb8 8. Ne2 {
when an exchange on d2 over the next few moves would transpose. But if he does
not hurry with that, he might have to give up the bishops' pair:} a5 9. O-O Na6
10. Nbc3 Nc5 11. b3 d6 12. a3 Bxc3 {Nikolaidis,I (2531)-Horvath,A (2504)
Panormo 2001 (½-½, 23)} 13. Bxc3 Bd7 (13... e4 14. b4 $14 Nd3 $6 15. Bxf6
gxf6 16. Nf4 Nxf4 17. exf4 O-O 18. Re1 f5 19. Qd4 $16) (13... a4 14. b4 Nb3 15.
Ra2 O-O 16. Nc1 Nxc1 17. Qxc1 $14 {planning f2-f4 when all White's pieces
would be optimally placed for the kingside attack, while the queenside still
remains "his" territory.}) 14. b4 Na4 15. Bd2 b5 16. Qc2 $14) 8. Qxd2 Nb8 9.
Nc3 d6 10. Nge2 O-O 11. h3 Ne8 (11... a5 12. g4 Na6 13. Ng3 Nc5 14. O-O-O Ne8
15. f4 f5 16. g5 Bd7 17. h4 $16 {with one-sided play, Brunello,S (2526)
-Karason,A (2324) Porto Mannu 2015 (1-0, 39)}) 12. f4 exf4 13. exf4 a5 14. O-O
Na6 15. Nd4 Qd8 16. Rae1 Nf6 17. g4 Re8 18. g5 Nd7 19. h4 $16 {Beliavsky,A 
(2710)-Gipslis, A (2465) Parnu 1997 (1-0, 31) Once again White is in absolute
control of the position.}) (6... d5 7. a3 Bxd2+ 8. Nxd2 O-O 9. Ne2 {transposes
below.}) (6... O-O 7. Ne2 d5 {is a deviation from the typical Bogo-Indian
structures.} (7... a5 8. Nbc3 Bxc3 ({If} 8... e5 9. O-O {Black has to count
with Nd5, which actually could follow at once.}) 9. Nxc3 e5 10. Nd5 (10. O-O $5
exd4 $6 11. exd4 Nxd4 $2 12. Bg5 Ne6 13. Nd5 Qd8 14. Nxf6+ gxf6 15. Bh6 Re8 16.
Qg4+ Kh8 17. Qh5 $18) 10... Nxd5 11. cxd5 Nb4 12. O-O (12. dxe5 Nd3+ 13. Ke2
Nxe5 {1-0 (37) Khairullin,I (2617)-Berescu,A (2486) Rijeka 2010}) 12... exd4
13. a3 dxe3 14. Bxe3 Na6 15. d6 $16) 8. a3 Bxd2+ 9. Nxd2 Rd8 (9... Na5 10. cxd5
exd5 11. Qc2 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gd2b3,Gb3c5] folloed by b2-b4 and Nb3.}) 10. O-O e5 {
Otherwise it would be difficult to find counterplay, but the white knights
will prove very well placed.} 11. cxd5 Nxd5 12. e4 Nf6 13. d5 Nb8 14. Nc3 (14.
Qc2 c6 15. Nc4 cxd5 16. exd5 Nxd5 17. Rfd1 Be6 18. Nc3 Nxc3 19. Rxd8+ Qxd8 20.
Bxb7 $16) 14... c6 15. Re1 Nbd7 16. Nc4 Nb6 17. Ne3 $14 {Papaioannou,I (2520)
-Mastrovasilis,A (2315) Athens 1998 (½-½, 61)}) 7. Nxd2 (7. Qxd2 d5 {would
require an additional tempo to defend or retrieve c4.}) 7... d6 8. Ne2 e5 9. d5
Nb8 10. Nc3 {We can see that the knights have reached comfortable positions
via unusual paths.} O-O (10... h5 11. h4 a5 12. Qc2 {Now and later this is an
important move. White prevents ...Bf5 which would more or less force him playing
e3-e4. It is better to keep the pawns as they are in order to avoid relative
weaknesses on dark squares.} Na6 13. a3 Nc5 14. b3 Ng4 15. O-O f5 16. b4 Na6 17.
Nf3 O-O (17... axb4 18. axb4 Nxb4 19. Rxa8 Nxc2 20. Rxc8+ Kd7 21. Rxh8 $18) 18.
Qb3 Bd7 19. Ng5 Kh8 20. Rac1 $16 {White has promising queenside play while on
the kingside Black mainly has weaknesses, Swiercz, D (2656)-Socko, B (2600)
Katowice 2016 (½-½, 51)}) (10... Bf5 {is premature due to} 11. Qb3 b6 12.
Qa4+ $14 {spoiling Black's coordiation.}) 11. O-O ({The right move order is} 
11. Qc2 $1 {transposing below.}) 11... a5 (11... Bf5 $1) 12. Qc2 $1 (12. a3 Bf5
(12... Bg4 {is less molesting. In fact it foces White stepping onto the right
path:} 13. Qc2 Nbd7 14. b4 $14) 13. e4 Bg4 14. f3 (14. Qc2 Na6 15. Rab1 Rfb8
16. b4 Qd8 17. Rfc1 axb4 18. axb4 c5 $11 {This is mainly good because the
g2-bishop has its path restricted.}) 14... Bd7 15. b4 Na6 $13 {Vaisser,A (2533)
-Bauer,C (2638) Mulhouse 2011 (½-½, 65)}) 12... Na6 13. a3 Bd7 14. Rab1 ({
More natural and better than} 14. Rfb1 Rfc8 15. Ra2 (15. b4 axb4 16. axb4 Nxb4
17. Qb3 Na6 18. Qxb7 Qd8 19. Rxa6 Rab8 20. Qa7 Ra8 $11) 15... c6 16. dxc6 Bxc6)
14... Rfc8 ({The typical} 14... Nc5 15. b4 axb4 16. axb4 Na4 {does not free
Black's position completely. White wins time for continuing his consistent
pawn attack.} 17. Nxa4 Bxa4 18. Qc3 Bd7 19. Ra1 h6 20. Rfc1 Rfc8 21. c5 Qe8 22.
Rxa8 Rxa8 23. Nc4 $14) 15. b4 axb4 16. axb4 c5 {With the long diagonal open,
this does not equalize.} 17. dxc6 Bxc6 (17... bxc6 18. Nde4 (18. b5 $5 Nc5 19.
Nb3 Nxb3 20. Qxb3 {also offers some chances but it is better not to hurry with
freeing the a6-knight, which may be hanging in some lines.}) 18... Nxe4 19.
Bxe4 h6 20. Rfd1 $14 {with pressure on d6 and c6 and the permanent threat
b4-b5.}) {Pogonina,N (2454)-Dzagnidze,N (2529) Tehran 2016 (1-0, 47)} 18. Nde4
$14 {White has all chances to get the control over the weak d5-square.} *

[Event "?"]
