1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Bxd2+ {This apparently simplistic line
has enjoyed some popularity lately. Decades ago, from the strong players, only
such a slow strategist as Ulf Andersson would be happy with Black's position.
The main merit of this line is that Black is absolved of any early worries
and can develop normally without wasting time. But the last move also helps
White developing and in the main line there may be some problems on dark
squares.} 5. Qxd2 O-O 6. Bg2 d5 {This is the modern trend.} ({White can answer
the solid} 6... d6 {with the usual plan:} 7. Nc3 e5 {There are many
alternatives here, but generally Black's plan is based on ...e6-e5. White's
policy would remain unchanged: keep the central tension and complete the
development with e2-e3, Nge2 and so on. Later he can choose the right moment
for d4-d5 or/and f2-f4.} 8. e3 exd4 (8... Nc6 9. Nge2 Bg4 10. h3 Bxe2 11. Nxe2
exd4 12. Nxd4 Qd7 13. O-O a5 14. Rad1 Rfe8 15. Nb5 Ne4 16. Qc2 f5 {Garcia,D 
(2455)-Fernandez Aguado, J (2320) Barcelona 1994 (1-0, 35) White has an obvious
advantage and the most radical way of trying making use of the favorable
moment is} 17. g4 $5 $16) 9. Qxd4 Nc6 10. Qd2 Ne5 11. b3 $14 {With space
advantage for White and little or now counterplay for Black.}) 7. Nf3 Nbd7 ({
The old-fashioned} 7... Qe7 8. O-O Rd8 {is not a very effective way of
preparing a counterplay, as it is too time wasting.} 9. Rd1 ({I prefer this
move order to} 9. Qc2 {planning Rd1 due to} c5 $5) 9... Nc6 ({A typical plan
in this line. If} 9... c5 10. cxd5 {White's pressure along the d-file forces
Black entering a passive Isolani position with} exd5 11. dxc5 Qxc5 12. Nc3 Nc6
13. Rac1 $14) 10. Qc2 Nb4 (10... Bd7 11. Nbd2 Be8 12. Rac1 Rac8 13. a3 Nb8 14.
b4 dxc4 15. Nxc4 $16 {Cheparinov,I (2684)-Halkias,S (2519) Doha 2014 (1-0, 60)}
) 11. Qb3 dxc4 12. Qxc4 c5 13. a3 Na6 14. Nc3 Bd7 15. Ne5 Be8 16. dxc5 Nxc5 17.
b4 $36 {Khalifman,A (2515)-Timoscenko,G (2490) Sverdlovsk 1987 (1-0, 36)}) 8.
O-O c6 (8... dxc4 {enjoys some popularity as an obstinate attempt at
simplifying and reaching the worse side of a draw.} 9. Rc1 ({This way of
retrieving the pawn is enabled by Black's early concessions. Later, if Black
opens the center, the rook may prove useful along the fourth rank. Black's
main defensive idea after the abstractly most desirable} 9. Na3 {is that the
white queen is hanging after} e5 10. dxe5 Nxe5 $1 {with chances to gradually
equalize.}) 9... Qe7 (9... c5 {leaves Black strongly underdeveloped:} 10. dxc5
Nxc5 11. Ne5 Nd5 12. Nxc4 b6 13. b4 Na4 14. e4 Nc7 15. e5 Qxd2 16. Nbxd2 Nd5
17. Nd6 Rb8 18. Bxd5 exd5 19. Rc7 $16 {Giri,A (2717)-Zontakh,A (2556) Plovdiv
2012 (1-0, 26)}) (9... e5 {does not work now because the queen is over defended
} 10. dxe5 Ng4 11. Qf4 $18) (9... b5 $2 10. Ne5 Nd5 11. Nc6 Qe8 12. a4 $16) (
9... Nb6 10. Na3 Ne4 11. Qc2 Nd6 12. Ne5 f6 13. Nexc4 Ndxc4 14. Nxc4 Qxd4 15.
Nxb6 cxb6 16. Qb3 $14) 10. Rxc4 c6 11. b3 ({A slightly mysterious move,
preparing Qb2 as an answer to a possible ...Rd8.} 11. Qf4 {eventually led to a
similar ending but in principle White wastes some time offering the
possibility of a queen exchange, instead of inviting Black to look for a way
to achieve that.} Re8 12. e4 e5 13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. Qxe5 Qxe5 15. Nxe5 Rxe5 16.
Nc3 Re7 17. Rd4 Be6 18. f4 Rd7 19. Rxd7 Nxd7 20. Rd1 $14 {Le,Q (2693)-Adams,M 
(2722) Istanbul 2012 (1-0, 46) and Black is still far from equality.}) ({Or if
} 11. Ne5 Rd8 {and the queen isses the b2-square.}) 11... Re8 (11... e5 12.
dxe5 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Qxe5 14. Nc3 Be6 15. Rd4 $14) 12. Ne5 Nd5 13. Qb2 ({It
would also make sense removing the rook from the exposed position with} 13. Rc1
f6 14. Nf3 e5 15. e4 N5b6 16. Qc3 $14 {followed by Nbd2}) 13... f6 14. Nxd7
Bxd7 15. Nd2 e5 16. dxe5 Qxe5 17. Qxe5 Rxe5 18. Ne4 Nb6 19. Rd4 Be6 20. Rad1
Bd5 21. Nc3 Bxg2 22. Kxg2 Rae8 23. e3 Kf7 24. a4 R8e7 25. b4 Na8 26. e4 $14 {
Meier,G (2640)-Naiditsch,A (2716) Baden-Baden 2013 (1-0, 47) In all these
games White's advantage is minimal, but it is suggestive that Black could not
reach a draw in any of them.}) (8... b6 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Nc3 Bb7 {leads to
some sort of Queen's Indian tabiya with hanging pawns against the fianchetto.
The main difference consists of the early bishops' exchange, which in
principle helped White's development. But on the other hand, Black has solved
his space problems, gaining free play along the e-file and the e7-square for
the queen. The conclusion is that White should act quickly to make use of his
better development.} 11. Ne5 ({Against slow play Black is likely to get an
entirely viable position:} 11. Rac1 Re8 12. Rfd1 c6 13. Qc2 Qe7 14. Nd2 Nf8 15.
e4 {Hard to find another active plan.} dxe4 16. Ndxe4 Ne6 17. Qa4 Nxe4 18. Bxe4
b5 $132 {Markus,R (2662)-Cori Tello,J (2609) Baku 2016 (0-1, 38)}) 11... Nxe5 (
11... Qe7 {allows a favourable regrouping:} 12. Nd3 Rfd8 13. Rac1 Nf8 14. b4
Ne6 15. e3 c6 16. Qb2 $16 {with a consistent minority's attack, Hera,I (2564)
-Sax,G (2436) Hungary 2013 (1-0, 32)}) 12. dxe5 Ne4 13. Nxe4 dxe4 14. Qc2 (14.
Qe3 Qd5 15. f4 $14 exf3 $2 16. Bxf3 $18) 14... Qd5 15. Qxc7 Rac8 16. Qd6 Qxd6
17. exd6 Rfd8 18. Rac1 $14 {Grabarczyk,M (2484)-Lentrodt,T (2282) Bad Wiessee
1999 (1-0, 45)}) (8... Qe7 {is an attempt at reaching the main line
continuation with a slightly different move order.} 9. Qf4 ({From the moves
tried in practice, this is my favorite, even though it was not tried at a high
level. But I also see no special reasons to continue in the spirit of the main
line with} 9. Ne5 {for instance} Nxe5 10. dxe5 Nd7 11. cxd5 exd5 12. Nc3 c6 13.
f4 $14) (9. Rc1 c6 {would more or less transpose to a just minimally better
line we wish voiding (see below).}) 9... c5 (9... dxc4 10. Qxc7 Qb4 11. Nbd2
Nb6 12. Qc5 Qxb2 13. Rfb1 Qc2 14. Rc1 Qa4 15. Nxc4 $16 {Manor,I (2270)-Csom,I 
(2505) Beersheba 1986 (0-1, 31)}) (9... c6 10. Nbd2 b6 11. e4 $14) 10. dxc5
Qxc5 (10... e5 11. Qe3 dxc4 12. Rc1 $14 {with just more pleasant play for
White.}) {1-0 (47) Dragun,K (2532)-Mirski,M (1864) Karpacz 2013} 11. cxd5 Nxd5
12. Qd2 $14 {White has wasted two tempi with his queen but he will get them
back by attacking the enemy queen and central knight (Rc1, e2-e4). As for the
rest, the play was opened in a moment when Blck is underdeveloped.}) 9. Ne5 $5 {
A relatively rare continuation, but a logical one, aiming at increasing White's
control on dark squares.} ({The modern main line goes} 9. Rc1 b6 10. cxd5 cxd5
11. Nc3 Ba6 {Optically WHite is doing very well, but due to the symmetrical
structure Black should be able to hold on to a draw with careful play.}) 9...
Nxe5 ({Black must pick up the gauntlet as after} 9... Qe7 10. f4 Rd8 11. Nc3
$14 {White consolidates his control in the center, Prasanna Raghuram, R (2410)
-Swayams,M (2445) Kolkata 2014 (½-½, 31)}) ({The awfully passive} 9... Qb6 {
deserves mentioning briefly, as it was played at 2700+ level.} 10. e3 Rd8 11.
Qc3 Nf8 12. c5 Qc7 13. Nd2 N6d7 14. Nd3 Ng6 15. f4 $14 {with one-sided play,
Adhiban,B (2567)-Alekseev,E (2710) Tromsoe 2013 (½-½, 41)}) 10. dxe5 Nd7 11.
f4 {The structure has turned non-symmetrical and White has hopes proving that
Black's bishop is "bad". Moreover, Black is also behind in development.} Nb6 ({
The principled but basically risky} 11... f6 {needs considering:} 12. cxd5 (12.
exf6 Nxf6 13. Nc3 Qe7 14. Rad1 Qc5+ 15. Qd4 Qxc4 16. Qxc4 dxc4 17. Rd2 Nd5 $13)
12... exd5 ({This is the most ambitious continuation for if} 12... cxd5 13.
exf6 Nxf6 14. Qd4 Bd7 15. Nc3 $14 {White consolidates his control over the
dark squares, De Abreu, R (2013)-Lkhagvasuren, T (2292) Al Ain 2013 (½-½, 79)})
13. e6 $1 Nb6 14. f5 Nc4 {White has enormous kingside space advantage and the
c8-bishop is immobile. But Black is going to win a pawn.} 15. Qc1 Qb6+ 16. Kh1
Qxb2 17. Qxb2 Nxb2 18. Nd2 Na4 19. Rac1 Nb6 20. Nb3 $14 {It is not clear yet
how Black will complete his development while White can prepare to open the
center with Rfd1 and e2-e4.}) ({Black does not gain anything by delaying
concrete action with} 11... Qe7 {as this gives White some time consolidating
on dark squares.} 12. Qd4 $5 $146 {Over-defending e5 and clearing the
d2-square for the knight.} f6 (12... c5 13. Qd3 {prematurely weakens Black's
centre.}) 13. Nd2 $14 fxe5 14. fxe5 Rxf1+ 15. Rxf1 {with all the chances for a
good ending.}) 12. Na3 Qe7 13. Rac1 a5 {Based on his solid structure, Black
tries creating counterplay without completing his development. Actually, there
is no clear clue about how he could do that.} (13... Rd8 14. Rfd1 Bd7 15. c5
Nc8 16. e4 $14 {Dorfman,J (2602)-Spassky,B (2551) France 2002 (½-½, 27)}) (
13... Nxc4 14. Nxc4 dxc4 15. Rxc4 $16) (13... Qc5+ 14. Kh1 Nxc4 15. Nxc4 dxc4
16. b3 b5 17. Qd6 $14) 14. Rfd1 (14. e3 $5 Na4 15. Qd4 Qb4 16. Rf2 $14) (14. c5
$6 Nd7 15. Qd4 f6 $132) 14... Na4 15. e4 Qb4 {White has several ways of
