1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 a5 {Strategically, this is the most
consistent way of defending the bishop, as White would not consider exchanging
it, which would only improve Black's structure (compare with ...cxb4 in line 1).
} 5. Bg2 O-O {Just one of the possible plans.} (5... d5 6. Nf3 O-O ({for the
critical} 6... dxc4 {see line 5.}) 7. O-O c6 (7... Nc6 {bears some optical
similarity with line 5, but delaying ...dxc4 actually leaves the knight
misplaced. Black usually heads for a Stonewall type of structure, but quite an
inflexible version of it.} 8. Qc2 Ne4 9. Rd1 {The most flexible move, inviting
Black showing his cards. Exchanges on d2 would just help White's development.}
f5 10. Nc3 Nxd2 {Otherwise White may continue with e2-e3, Ne2, Rac1 and so on.}
11. Rxd2 dxc4 {Reckoning with the fact that after a later cxd5 Black might
have problems defending the d5-pawn and the d5-pawn. In this structure, he
should have ...Nd7 and ...c6, but it is too late for second thoughts. In
McDougall, W-Hanley, C (2415) Eastleigh 2011 (0-1, 36) White's strongest
continuation would have been:} 12. a3 Bd6 13. e4 $16) 8. Qc2 Nbd7 9. Bf4 {
This is closely related to the closed systems.} Be7 {Evacuating the bishop
before White traps it with c4-c5.} 10. Nbd2 Nh5 (10... b6 11. e4 $14) 11. Be3
Bd6 (11... f5 12. Nb3 $1 {The shortest way to d3, from where the knight will
increase White's control over e5.} a4 13. Nc1 Nb6 14. Ne5 dxc4 15. Nxc4 Nd5 16.
Bd2 c5 17. dxc5 Bxc5 18. Nd3 Ba7 19. Nce5 $16 {Stohl,I (2560)-Chandler,M (2590)
Germany 1992 (1-0, 60)}) 12. Nb3 Qe7 13. Nc1 b5 14. c5 Bc7 15. Bg5 f6 16. Bd2
f5 17. Nd3 Bb7 18. Nfe5 $14 {Tomashevsky,E (2724)-Riazantsev,A (2651)
Novosibirsk 2016 (½-½, 44) White is in complete control and can prepare
breaking ith either e2-e4 or g3-g4.}) (5... d6 6. e3 {The familiar reaction to
Black's play on dark squares.} e5 7. Ne2 O-O 8. O-O exd4 (8... Bxd2 {Shulman,Y
(2551)-Gulko,B (2606) Philadelphia 2001 (½-½, 26)} 9. Qxd2 $14 {followed by
Nbc3.}) (8... c6 9. Bc1 $1 exd4 10. exd4 d5 11. c5 a4 12. a3 Ba5 13. Qxa4 $16 {
Loetscher,R (2437)-Prohaszka,P (2591) Germany 2016 (½-½, 76)}) 9. exd4 (9.
Nxd4 {is equally good.} Nbd7 10. Qc2 Nc5 11. Nc3 Re8 12. b3 a4 13. Nd5 Bxd2 14.
Qxd2 c6 15. Nxf6+ Qxf6 16. b4 $14 {Burmakin,V (2519)-Ikonnikov,V (2580)
Schwaebisch Gmuend 2006 (1-0, 46)}) 9... d5 (9... Re8 10. Be3 c5 11. h3 $14)
10. cxd5 Nxd5 11. Nbc3 Be6 12. Nf4 Nxf4 13. Bxf4 Bxc3 (13... c6 14. d5 cxd5 15.
Nxd5 $16) 14. bxc3 c6 {Tazbir,M (2497)-Stupak,K (2456) Litomysl 2009 (1-0, 44)}
15. Qd3 $16 {/\c3-c4. With two strong bishops, the better structure and some
lead in development.}) 6. Nf3 b6 $5 {Transposing to a Queen's Indian system} (
6... d6 7. O-O Bxd2 (7... Nbd7 $6 8. Bg5 d5 9. c5 $1 {forces Black giving up
his a-pawn to savethe bishop.}) 8. Qxd2 Nc6 (8... Nbd7 9. Nc3 e5 10. Rad1 Re8
