1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 a5 5. Bg2 d5 6. Nf3 dxc4 {This can lead
to either a traditional system or a fashionable one.} 7. Qc2 Nc6 {This is the
classical treatment of this variation.} 8. Qxc4 Qd5 9. Qd3 (9. Qxd5 exd5 {
would unnecessarily clear the path for the c8-bishop and help Black fighting
for space in the center .}) 9... Qe4 {I used playing this with black, under the
impression of some old games of Polugaevsky and Taimanov. Black has two main
alternatives:} (9... Qf5 10. Qxf5 exf5 {This ensures Black some stability on
light squares but leaves White with an advantage in the center.} 11. O-O Be6
12. a3 Bd6 13. Nc3 h6 14. Rfc1 Ke7 15. e3 a4 {Shalimov,V (2424)-Eingorn,V 
(2600) Alushta 2004 (½-½, 17)} 16. Be1 $14 {/\Nd2}) (9... O-O {This requires
careful play with black as his queen gets into some danger.} 10. Nc3 Qh5 (10...
Bxc3 11. bxc3 Qe4 12. Qb5 a4 13. Rc1 Qd5 14. Qb1 Qc4 15. e4 Na5 16. Bf4 b6 17.
Ne5 Qa6 18. Bf1 Qb7 19. Bd3 $16 {Seres,L (2457)-Thinius,M (2345) Deizisau 2014
(0-1, 31)}) 11. h3 Rd8 12. g4 Qg6 13. Qxg6 hxg6 14. e3 a4 15. a3 Bf8 {Atalik,S
(2549)-Speelman,J (2623) Germany 2000 (½-½, 46)} 16. g5 Nd5 17. Ne4 $14) 10.
Qxe4 Nxe4 11. Bxb4 $1 {This is one of the cases when exchanging is not only
possible but also favorable for White.} ({The old main line went} 11. a3 Nxd2
12. Nbxd2 Be7 {when the bishops' pair ensures Black chances for counterplay
despite White's space advantage.}) 11... axb4 {This is the most principled
answer but as strange as it may seem the pawn may turn into a weakness.
Additionally, White gets the b3-square for his knight.} ({WHite ca neutralize
Black's initiative after} 11... Nxb4 12. O-O $1 f6 (12... Nc2 $2 13. Ne1 Nxa1
14. Bxe4 $18) (12... Ke7 13. Rc1 Na6 14. Ne5 Nd6 15. Nd2 Rd8 16. e3 Ra7 $5 17.
Bf1 Ne8 18. a3 Nb8 19. Rc2 Nd7 {Vaulin,A (2540)-Faibisovich,V (2415) Swidnica
2000 (½-½, 26)} 20. f4 $14) (12... Nd6 13. Nc3 Nd5 14. Rac1 Nxc3 15. Rxc3 c6
16. e3 Ke7 17. Ne5 Bd7 18. Rd1 Rhc8 {Biriukov,O (2330)-Krogius,N (2490)/St
Petersburg 1996} 19. f4 f6 20. Nd3 Be8 21. Nc5 $14) 13. Rc1 c6 14. Nc3 Nd6 15.
e4 {Black's position looks terrible but without queens it is quite resilient.
STill, WHite keeps the control for a long time.} Ke7 16. a3 Na6 17. e5 (17. Re1
$1) 17... Nf7 {Beliavsky,A (2640)-Ljubojevic,L (2590) Linares 1991 (0-1, 39)}
18. Re1 $14) 12. Nbd2 {Gaining time for the development based on the exposed
position of the enemy knight.} Nxd2 (12... Nf6 {prevents the king's activation
on the optimal d2-square but wastes another tempo.} 13. O-O Ke7 14. Nb3 Bd7 15.
Rfc1 Rhc8 (15... Ra4 16. Ne5 $16) 16. Ne1 Ra4 17. Nd3 (17. Nc5 Nxd4) 17... Rca8
18. Bxc6 $1 Bxc6 19. Nbc5 Rxa2 20. Rxa2 Rxa2 21. Nxb7 $1 Be4 22. Nbc5 $5 $14 {
with a very pleasant ending for White due to Black's queenside weaknesses.}) (
12... Nd6 {is similar:} 13. O-O Ke7 14. Rfc1 f6 15. e3 Bd7 16. Ne1 Rhc8 17. Nd3
e5 18. d5 Nd8 19. Nxb4 $16 {Giemsa,S (2284)-Lagunow,A (2438)/Berlin 2007/EXT
2008 (1/2, 71)}) 13. Kxd2 {The white king feels safe in the centre.} Bd7 ({
Black's counterplay after} 13... Ke7 14. Rhc1 Rd8 {is ineffective:} 15. e3 $14
e5 (15... Bd7 16. Ne1 Ra4 17. b3 Ra5 18. Bxc6 Bxc6 19. Nd3 {wins the b4-pawn
and defends a2 in time.}) 16. Rxc6 $1 bxc6 17. Nxe5 $16 {Sosonko,G (2505)
-Herzog,A (2210)/Lucerne 1982/EXT 97-B (1-0, 45)}) 14. Rhc1 Ke7 (14... f6 {
prevents Ne5 but weakens the structure. Besides, the white knight can reach d3.
} 15. Ne1 $5 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Gg2c6,Ge1d3]} (15. e3 Ke7 16. Ne1 $14 {[%csl Gb4]
[%cal Ge1d3,Gg2c6]}) 15... Nxd4 16. Bxb7 Ra7 17. Bg2 Ke7 18. e3 Nf5 19. Nd3 Rb8
20. Rc4 b3 21. a3 $16 {Black's queenside pawns are very vulerable.}) 15. Ne5 $1
$16 Nxd4 (15... Nxe5 16. dxe5 c6 17. Rc4 $16) 16. Rxc7 Rhd8 {Biriukov,O (2255)
-Faibisovich,V (2455) St Petersburg 1995 (1-0, 32) The simplest now is:} 17.
Rxb7 $16 *

