1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 a5 5. Bg2 d5 6. Nf3 dxc4 7. Qc2 Bxd2+ {
This is the modern treatment of this line, advocated by Topalov. ***There are
also a few more modern lines worth mentioning even though they occur less
frequently.} (7... b5 $6 {weakens the queenside for nothing.} 8. a4 c6 9. axb5
Bxd2+ (9... Nd5 10. bxc6 Nxc6 11. O-O $16) 10. Nfxd2 Qxd4 11. Qxc4 Qb6 12. Nc3
Bb7 13. Na4 Qc7 14. b6 $18 {Gulko,B (2610)-Ljubojevic,L (2625) Linares 1990 
(1-0, 78)}) (7... b6 {requires some accuracy for getting a clear advantage.} 8.
O-O ({Paradoxically} 8. Ne5 {is slightly premature:} Ra7 {With the d4-pawn
hanging White needs forcing matters.} 9. Bxb4 axb4 10. Qxc4 Qd6 11. Nd3 Ba6 12.
Qxb4 Bxd3 13. Qxd6 cxd6 14. exd3 d5 {As proven in several games, the weakness
on d4 prevents White from enjoying his extra pawn.}) 8... O-O (8... Bb7 {
removes the potential threat ...Ba6 allowing} 9. Bxb4 axb4 10. Qxc4 Na6 11.
Nbd2 O-O 12. Rfd1 Qe7 13. Ne5 Bxg2 14. Kxg2 c5 {Ribli,Z (2595)-Lekic,D (2389)
Neum 2004 (1-0, 25)} 15. dxc5 bxc5 16. Ndf3 $16) {Kezin,R (2455)-Khismatullin,
D (2628) Sochi 2017 (0-1, 38)} 9. Ne5 Ra7 10. Rd1 $14 {/+/- with the usual
space advantage.}) (7... Ra6 $5 {was introduced by the ever creative
Kortschnoj in a game against myself.} 8. Bxb4 ({I continued with} 8. Na3 Bxa3
9. bxa3 b5 10. Rb1 Bd7 11. Ne5 O-O 12. a4 b4 13. Qxc4 Bxa4 14. a3 {and now in
Marin,M (2551)-Kortschnoj,V (2611) Reggio Emilia 2008 (½-½, 58) Black could
have obtained at least enough counterplay with} Rd6 15. e3 Nbd7) 8... axb4 9.
Qxc4 Rc6 10. Qb5 $1 {Pinning the rook to gain a tempo for developing.} Bd7 11.
O-O Rb6 {Batchuluun,T (2432)-Maletin,P (2573) Novokuznetsk 2008 (0-1, 51)} 12.
Qc5 $14 {/+/- Instead of queenside counterplay, Black has just an additional
weakness on b4.}) 8. Qxd2 c6 9. a4 Ne4 {This plan became popular after Anand's
convincing win over Topalov below.} (9... b5 10. Na3 $5 $146 Bd7 {There is
nothing better than this awkward move, which places the bishop in the way of
its colleagues.} (10... Ba6 {leaves the c6-square vulnerable, allowing} 11. Ne5
Nd5 12. Nxc6 Nxc6 13. axb5 $16 {White retrieves the pawn, maintaining the
better structure and a strong bishop.}) 11. Ne5 Nd5 {This is a first critical
moment. The knight move looks natural, but causes a big loss of time, allowing
White increase his domination in the center. Besides, the kingside defense is
weakened, which will prove a decisive factor in the end.} 12. e4 Nb4 {The
evaluation of this move depends on the depth of the examination. Optically
speaking, this looks like a great square for the knight. Practically, it does
not do much, failing to defend Black's own pawn chain or put pressure on a4,
in order to force the releasing of the tension. Concrete analysis proves that
Black could not play the more desirable moves, though:} (12... Nb6 {attacks a4,
more or less forcing} 13. axb5 {, but this works out well for White because
the knight is vulnerable on b6:} cxb5 14. Nxd7 Qxd7 15. Qg5 Qxd4 (15... O-O {
is relatively better, with just a bad position after} 16. Qxb5 {, when} Qxd4 $2
{drops a piece to} 17. Rd1 $18) 16. Rd1 Qf6 17. Qxb5+ N8d7 (17... N6d7 {
loses a rook to} 18. e5 $18) 18. Nxc4 $18 {and one of the knights will be lost.
}) (12... Nc7 {would be a good consolidating move if Black could get castled
in time, but} 13. d5 $16 {In case of general exchanges, the f7-square and the
a8-rook would be forked by the queen. After the text move, the possibility of.
..Nd3+ forces White to get castled before initiating active operations, but,
as mentioned before, the long-term effects of the knight's presence on b4 are
unfavorable for Black.}) 13. O-O O-O 14. Rfd1 {White has completed his
development and all his pieces are placed on optimal squares. One may argue
that the queen's rook and knight could desire a better fate, but their latent
pressure against the b5-pawn and along the a-file is quite useful.
Anticipating a bit, it will not take long before these pieces will emerge into
play very effectively.} Be8 {Black evacuates the d-file anticipating the
central break.} (14... N8a6 $6 {turns} 15. d5 $16 {even stronger than in the
game.}) (14... Qe7 $5 15. Qe3 {renewing the threat of d5.} Be8 16. d5 f6 (16...
Qd6 17. Nxc6 N8xc6 18. dxc6 Qxc6 19. axb5 $16) 17. dxc6 (17. Nxc6 N8xc6 18.
dxc6 bxa4 19. e5 $14) 17... fxe5 18. axb5 Bxc6 19. bxc6 N8xc6 20. Rac1 Nd4 21.
Nxc4 $14 {Black's knights stand actively, but they are not 100% stable because both the a5 and the e5 pawns are weak.}) 15. d5 $1 Qd6 {Unlike in the
previous game, Black prevents the opening of the long diagonal and also
defends e6. But now his queenside fortress crumbles down.} (15... Qb6 16. dxe6
fxe6 17. Qd6 $16 {leads to a familiar picture, where the e6-pawn is a
permanent source of worries.}) ({Or if} 15... f6 16. dxc6 Qxd2 17. Rxd2 fxe5
18. axb5 {the b8-knight is trapped. Black can return the piece, of course, but
after, say,} Bxc6 19. bxc6 N8xc6 20. Nxc4 $14 {the weaknesses on a5, e5 and e6
leave him struggling.}) 16. Ng4 {[%cal Ge4e5] Threatening e4-e5.} Qc5 17. Ne3 {
The knight has reached a stable square, from where it consolidates White's
control over the d5-square and increases the pressure against the c4-pawn.}
N8a6 {Finally, Black has started developing. However, this is not done in an
optimal way. The knight would be so much more useful closer to the d4-square,
while on the edge of the board it is passive and causes difficulties with
keeping a5 well defended.} 18. dxc6 bxa4 {Black's extra pawn on the a-file
will not be too threatening in the middlegame, but Topalov probably wanted to
shield his other a-pawn with it's colleague.} ({After} 18... Bxc6 19. axb5 Bxb5
20. Naxc4 Bxc4 21. Rac1 $16 {The a5-pawn would be more vulnerable, but Black
would have exchanged one pair of minor pieces. All in all, the objective
evaluation of the position would remain the same.}) 19. Naxc4 Bxc6 20. Rac1 {
[%cal Gc4d6,Ge4e5,Ge3g4,Gd2g5] Black's extra pawn is not relevant while White
has such threats as Nd6, Ng4 combined with e4-e5 and Qg5. Anand, V (2787)
-Topalov,V (2805) Sofia 2010.}) 10. Qf4 $5 ({Black's main plan consists of
forcing the exchange of one night on White's way to retrieve the pawn. Here is
a draft optimal line for him:} 10. Qc1 Nd6 11. Nfd2 Na6 12. Na3 Nb4 13. O-O O-O
14. Rd1 b6 15. Ndxc4 Nxc4 16. Nxc4 Ba6 $11 {Due to the strong b4-knight it is
not clear whether the 4-pawn is a strength or a target. The recommended last
move tries maintaining the initiative for White.}) 10... Qb6 {Trying to make
use of the queen early departure from the queenside.} ({If Black plays in the
same way as in the line above, White can set up an annoying pressure.} 10... Nd6
11. Na3 Na6 12. Ne5 O-O 13. O-O Nb4 14. Rfd1 {It appears that playing ...b7-b6
is not so simple.} f6 ({A necessary weakening.} 14... Qc7 15. Nexc4 $16 {
leaves the black queen and knight hanging.}) 15. Qc1 $1 (15. Nexc4 {
prematurely releases the pressure.} Nxc4 16. Nxc4 b6 17. Rd2 Ba6 {Horvath,J 
(2528)-Meszaros,T (2409) Zalakaros 2016 (1-0, 28)}) 15... Qc7 (15... Qe7 16.
Nexc4 Nxc4 17. Nxc4 Qc7 18. e4 b6 19. e5) 16. Nexc4 Nxc4 17. Qxc4 b6 18. Rac1
$16 {Black has problems defending c6 and e6. Most likely, he will never play ..
.Ba6.}) 11. Ne5 $5 $146 {The most radical way of fighting for the initiative.}
Qb4+ (11... f6 12. Qxe4 Qxb2 13. O-O Qxa1 14. Nxc4 {[%cal Gc4b6] /\Nb6} Na6 15.
Nb6 Nc7 (15... Rb8 16. Nxc8 Rxc8 17. Qxe6+ Kd8 18. Qb3 {/\Nc3} Qxd4 19. Rd1 $18
) 16. Nd2 Qc3 17. Ndc4 $14 {White is dominating while the black queen is still
