1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 c5 {Time has come to focus on a series of lines
resulting when White rejects Black's invitation to a Benoni. I would refrain
from 4.d5 not only because this would cause some conflict with my Benoni
articles (in principle, there is always a way), but mainly because I firmly
believe that the fianchetto system is one of the least dangerous for Black in
the Benoni. White could avoid transposing to these lines in several ways.
First of all, if Black starts the game with the Queen's Gambit move order he
cannot transpose to the lines examined below. In his turn, White could use the
Reti or English move order or else play 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 e6 3.Nf3 and only after
3...d5 switch to 4.g3, but this latter would allow 3...b6 of course.} 4. Nf3
cxd4 ({Just a few words about} 4... b6 {which has every right of being
considered as dubious as it looks. White has several ways of reacting.} 5. Bg2
({This transposes to a Queen's Indian sideline, but simpler is} 5. d5 exd5 6.
cxd5 d6 7. Nc3 g6 8. Bg2 Bg7 9. O-O O-O {This transposes to a 9...b6
fianchetto Benoni, a line which has enjoyed some popularity recently.
Personally, I find Black's counterplay too slow.} 10. Bf4 Ba6 11. Re1 b5 12. a3
$14 {preparing e2-e4-e5 but also b2-b4.}) 5... Bb7 6. d5 exd5 7. Nh4 ({Recent
games have shown that} 7. cxd5 Bxd5 8. Nc3 Bc6 9. e4 {offers White strong
initiative for the pawn.}) 7... g6 8. Nc3 Bg7 9. O-O O-O 10. Bg5 h6 11. Bxf6
Qxf6 12. Rb1 $5 $146 {Defending b2 in order to prepare the piece invasion on
d5 starting with Bxd5.}) 5. Nxd4 {This is our starting point. Strictly
speaking, the position could be classified as a Symmetrical English, but this
does not change the essence of the matter: the Catalan bishop remains our main
pride.} d5 {Apparently this is a transposition to a very passive (for Black)
Catalan, but the point is that White cannot react in the center before he
develops his bishop.} 6. Bg2 ({Speciffically:} 6. cxd5 Qxd5 $1 $15) 6... e5 {
But now cxd5 was becoming a threat, so the last move is the only principled.}
7. Nf3 {The classical approach and the sounder one. White has also tried other
knight retreats, aimed at keeping the f-pawn's and g2-bishop's paths clear in
order to win the d4-pawn with f2-f4 and Bxc6, but all these weaken the
kingside offering Black excellent compensation. The main move keeps an eye not
only on d4 but also on e5, preparing to open the center with e2-e3.} d4 8. O-O
Nc6 9. e3 {This is White's only active plan as he cannot allow Black
consolidate his center. After the exchange on d4, Black will get a passed pawn,
which White will try proving weak, using his piece activity (not least that of
his Catalan bishop). Black has three main possibilities: 9...d3, 9...Bc5 and 9.
..Be7. The latter is the most consistent and will be examined in Line 16.} Bc5
{Optically this looks the most active but has the drawback of leaving the
e-file vulnerable. We can feel the spirit of the reversed Benoni, as Black
misses one tempo to consolidate his space gainings optimally.} (9... d3 {
is a provocative move I analyzed with Judit Polgar more than a decade ago,
before her Candidates' match with Bareev.} 10. e4 $5 {A relatively new idea
and in principle the safest one. White immediately cuts the daring pawn off
his colleagues.} ({The traditional answer against which we focused during our
analysis is} 10. Nc3 Bb4 11. Bd2 O-O 12. a3 Bxc3 13. Bxc3 Ne4 14. Bxe5 Bg4 15.
Bd4 Ng5 16. Bc3 Rc8 17. b4 Re8 18. h4 Ne4 19. Bb2 Qd7 20. Qc1 d2 {with huge
complications in which Judit once again proved her brilliant tactical
intuition, Gelfand,B (2737)-Polgar,J (2707) Wijk aan Zee 2008 (0-1, 40)}) 10...
Bg4 {Black's best defence. The threat ...Nd4, strongly restricting White,
forces him wasting a tempo on the next move.} (10... Be6 11. Nc3 {Heading for
the d5-square.} Bxc4 (11... Qd7 12. Nd5 Nxe4 13. Qxd3 f5 14. Be3 O-O-O 15. Rfd1
Kb8 16. Qe2 Qf7 17. Rac1 Bd6 $16 {½-½ Kohlweyer,B (2463)-Hracek,Z (2629) Bad
Wiessee 1999} 18. b4 Bxd5 19. Rxd5 Nxb4 20. Rb5 $18) 12. Qa4 Ba6 13. Nxe5 Qd4
14. Nxc6 Qxa4 15. Nxa4 d2 (15... bxc6 16. Bd2 Nd7 17. e5 Rc8 18. Rfe1 $16 {
Matozo,P (1706)-Bulgarini Torres,M (2287) ICCF email 2008 (1-0, 37)}) 16. Rd1
dxc1=Q 17. Raxc1 bxc6 18. e5 Nd5 19. Rxc6 Bb5 20. Bxd5 Bxa4 21. b3 $18 Bb5 $6
22. Rc7 $1 Kd8 23. Rxf7 Rb8 24. Bc6+ Kc8 25. Be4 Rb6 26. Bf5+ Kb8 27. Rd8# {
A beautiful attack worked out together with my pupil Alexandru Stanciu.}) (
10... Nxe4 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. Bxe4 Bg4 13. Qa4+ Qd7 14. Qxd7+ Kxd7 15. Bf4 $14 {
White will most likely win the d3-pawn.}) 11. h3 Bxf3 (11... Be6 12. Nc3 {
is similar to 10...Be6.}) 12. Qxf3 Qd4 13. Rd1 Rd8 14. Nc3 Qxc4 15. Bf1 Qe6 {
Hunger,H (2422)-Hanen,B (2341) ICCF email 2009 (½-½, 56)} 16. Nb5 $5 $146 {
White, of course, has more than one way to retrieve the pawn and keep the more
pleasant play due to his two bishops, but it does not hurt spoiling Blck's
coordination a bit, using the slight advance in development.} Rc8 (16... Bd6
17. Bg5 $14) (16... Rd7 17. Rxd3 a6 18. Rxd7 Qxd7 19. Nc3 Nd4 20. Qd1 h6 21.
Be3 Bc5 22. Bg2 O-O 23. Rc1 Ba7 24. Kh2 $14) 17. Be3 a6 18. Nc3 Be7 19. Rxd3
$14) ({The minor aternative} 9... Bg4 {also needs mentioning.} 10. exd4 (10. h3
$5 Bxf3 11. Bxf3) 10... e4 (10... Nxd4 11. Nbd2 Bc5 12. h3 Nxf3+ 13. Nxf3 Qxd1
14. Rxd1 Bxf3 15. Bxf3 $14) (10... exd4 11. Qb3 Qd7 12. Bf4 {/\Ne5.} Bxf3 13.
Bxf3 Be7 14. Nd2 O-O 15. Ne4 $14 {Taylor,G (2325)-Garcia,G (2505) Toronto 1998
(0-1, 35)}) 11. d5 $5 $146 {A promising piece sacrifice, leaving White with a
dangerous central pawn mass.} Ne5 (11... exf3 12. Re1+ Be7 13. h3 fxg2 14. hxg4
O-O 15. dxc6 bxc6 16. Nd2 $14) (11... Ne7 12. Nbd2 $16 {leaves Black
completely paralyzed.}) 12. Re1 Bd6 13. h3 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 exf3 15. c5 {Black
has nothing better than returning the piece.} O-O 16. cxd6 $14) 10. exd4 exd4
11. Re1+ Be6 12. Ng5 {This is the point. Black will now have chronical
weaknesses on light squares.} O-O 13. Nxe6 fxe6 14. Nd2 {Optically White's
position is very pleasant, but he needs certain accuracy, as f2 may be hanging
in some lines and his development is slightly delayed due to the maneuver
Ng5xe6. It makes no sense taking on e6, the essential thing is to set up the
perfect blockade on light squares and then the position would be strategically
winning.} Qd6 {The most natural move, keeping the queen central.} (14... Qb6
15. Nb3 $1 {A well-timed deviation from the main plan.} (15. Ne4 Nxe4 16. Bxe4
d3 {offers Black too much counterplay.}) 15... Rae8 16. Bg5 e5 (16... d3 {
Eidelson,R (2192)-Khmelnitski,A (2486) St Petersburg 2005 (½-½, 33)} 17. Be3
Bxe3 18. Rxe3 Nb4 19. Rb1 Nxa2 20. c5 $16) 17. a3 $5 {Preparing the knight's
absolute stability on d3 and also the usual queenside play with b2-b4.} Kh8 18.
Nc1 $16 a5 19. Bxf6 gxf6 20. Nd3 {Black has no way of putting his center into
motion and is doomed to a stable blockade. For instance} Bd6 21. b4 $1 Bb8 22.
Qh5 Qc7 23. f4 $16) (14... e5 {does not bring in anything positive.} 15. Ne4
Nxe4 16. Bxe4 Qf6 17. Rf1 Rad8 18. a3 d3 (18... a5 19. Qg4 h6 20. Bd2 $16) 19.
Be3 Nd4 20. Kg2 Kh8 21. Qxd3 Nf5 22. Qe2 Nxe3+ 23. fxe3 $16 {Sygulski,A (2410)
-Xu,J Thessaloniki 1984 (1-0, 44)}) (14... d3 {forces White being accurate,
but objectively it is premature:} 15. Nb3 Bd4 (15... Nd7 16. Rf1 Qb6 17. Bf4 e5
18. Nxc5 Nxc5 19. Be3 $14 Nd4 20. Bxd4 exd4 21. Qd2 a5 22. Rae1 $14) ({One
important point behind White's previous move is that} 15... Bxf2+ $2 16. Kxf2
Qb6+ {fails to} 17. c5 $1 $18) 16. Be3 Bxb2 17. Rb1 Bc3 18. Rf1 Bb4 19. Nc1 (
19. Bc5 {may be an even better way of retrieving the pawn:} Rf7 20. Bxc6 Bxc5
21. Nxc5 bxc6 22. Qxd3 $16) 19... d2 20. Nb3 Rf7 21. Nxd2 Bxd2 22. Qxd2 Qxd2
23. Bxd2 $14 {Adamski,J (2425)-Szymczak,Z (2460) Piotrkow Trybunalski 1983 
(½-½, 25) with a very pleasant ending for White.}) 15. Ne4 Nxe4 16. Bxe4 d3 {
The only attempt at counterplay.} (16... e5 17. a3 a5 {Rashkovsky,N (2520)
-Gorshkov,A Sverdlovsk 1979 (½-½, 27)} 18. Qh5 g6 19. Qg4 $16) (16... h6 {
is not exactly what Black's position needs, as he already has many weak light
squares.} 17. Bd3 Rf6 18. a3 a5 19. Qe2 a4 20. Bd2 Bb6 {Ehlvest,J (2615)
-Topalov,V (2630) Novgorod 1995 (½-½, 49)} 21. Qe4 $5 {Even if Black
survives the middlegame, the endgame would be a sheer disaster.}) 17. Qh5 $1 {
The only move avoiding trouble, but quite a strong one. The best defence is
the (counter)attack.} (17. Rf1 $2 Bxf2+ 18. Rxf2 Rxf2 19. Kxf2 Qd4+ 20. Kf3
Rf8+ 21. Bf4 Ne5+) (17. Bf4 $2 Rxf4 18. gxf4 d2 19. Re2 Rd8 20. Bg2 Qxf4 $17) (
17. Be3 d2 18. Re2 Bxe3 19. Rxe3 Rad8 $15) 17... Bxf2+ 18. Kg2 h6 (18... g6 19.
Bxg6 hxg6 20. Qxg6+ Kh8 21. Qh6+ Kg8 22. Rxe6 $18) 19. Bxh6 Bxe1 20. Bh7+ Kxh7
21. Bf4+ Kg8 22. Bxd6 Rf2+ 23. Kh3 d2 24. Rd1 Nd4 25. Qg4 Nf3 26. Qxe6+ Kh8 27.
Qd5 $16 {Miton,K (2581)-Ulybin,M (2516) La Laguna 2010 (1-0, 52) White has a
material advantage and due to his mobile queen his attack remains more
dangerous than Black's.} *

