[Annotator "GM Mihail Marin"]
[PlyCount "33"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 c5 4. Nf3 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Qc7 {Black attacks the c4-pawn
aiming at spoiling White's natural development based on Nc3.} 6. Nd2 {This
developing move is the most constructive way of defending the pawn. I have
several times defended Black's point of view when White simply sacrificed it,
as Black has not done so many commitments to be in real danger.} Nc6 {This
looks like a logical reaction as White has obstructed his own queen.} (6... b6
{is a continuation to my taste, transposing to some sort of English Hedgehog,
which I successfully met with... White.} 7. Bg2 Bb7 8. Nb5 Qc8 9. e4 a6 10. Nc3
d6 11. O-O Be7 12. b3 O-O (12... b5 13. Ba3 {prevents the blocking ...b5-b4
inviting Black to activate the d2-knight with ...bxc4 (after for instance Rc1).
}) 13. Bb2 Nbd7 14. Qe2 {If compared to a normal Hedgehog the knight stands on
d2 instead of d4. This means e4 is safely defended and there is no danger of ..
.e6-e5 after f2-f4.} Re8 (14... Qc7 15. f4 Rac8 16. Rf2 Rfe8 17. Raf1 Bf8 18.
g4 $14) 15. f4 e5 $5 {Nevertheless! Black tries reducing White's dynamic
potential.} (15... Bf8 16. Rac1 Qc7 17. g4 h6 18. Rf2 g6 19. Nf1 Bg7 20. Ng3
$14) (15... b5 16. cxb5 axb5 17. Nxb5 Qc2 18. Bxf6 Bxf6 19. Rfc1 Qb2 20. Qd1
Rxa2 21. Rxa2 Qxa2 22. Nxd6 $18) 16. Rac1 (16. f5 b5 17. cxb5 axb5 18. Nxb5 Qc2
$132) 16... exf4 ({Obviously a concession, but otherwise Black would be buried
alive after} 16... Bf8 17. f5 $16) 17. gxf4 Qd8 18. Bf3 {Preparing Kh1, Rg1
with a strong attack.} Nc5 (18... Bf8 19. Qg2 Nc5 20. e5 Bxf3 21. Nxf3 $16) (
18... b5 19. Kh1 Bf8 20. Qg2 $16) 19. b4 Ne6 20. Bg2 (20. Qe3 $5) 20... Bf8 21.
Nd5 Nd7 22. e5 (22. Rc3 $5) 22... b5 (22... Qh4 23. Rc3) 23. f5 Nc7 (23... Ng5
24. h4 Nxe5 25. hxg5 Nxc4 26. Qg4 Nxb2 27. g6 fxg6 28. fxg6 h6 29. Rf7 $16) 24.
e6 $18 {At this moment White has a decisive attack. I missed several wins and
eventually lost after pushing too hard in my own second time trouble, Marin,M 
(2539)-Lupulescu,C (2620) Calimanesti 2017 (0-1, 73)}) (6... Bb4 {Combining
this with ...Qc7 is not typical nor popular, but playable nevertheless.} 7. Qc2
(7. a3 Qxc4 {does not seem to offer White more than reasonable compensation
for the pawn.}) 7... Nc6 (7... e5 8. Nb5 Qc6 9. e4 $14 Nxe4 10. Bg2 d5 11. O-O
Bxd2 12. Bxd2 a6 13. Qa4 Nxd2 14. Bxd5 Qc5 15. Rfd1 O-O 16. Rxd2 Bd7 17. Re1
Bc6 18. Qa3 $16) 8. Nb5 Qb6 $5 $146 ({More natural and better than} 8... Qb8 9.
Bg2 a6 10. Nc3 Qe5 {Kappeler,K (2238)-Goldstern,F (2302) Switzerland 2017 
(½-½, 64)} 11. O-O Nd4 12. Qd3 Bxc3 13. e3 Bxb2 14. Bxb2 Ne2+ 15. Qxe2 Qxb2
16. c5 $16) 9. Bg2 d5 10. O-O O-O (10... dxc4 11. a4 $14 {/\Nxc4.}) 11. Nb3 a6
(11... Ne5 12. Bf4 Nxc4 13. Nc7 Bd7 14. Nxa8 Rxa8 15. a3 Bf8 16. Nd2 $14) 12.
Be3 (12. cxd5 exd5 13. Nc3 Be6 14. Be3 d4 15. Na4 Qa7 16. Bg5 Nd7 17. Rfd1 Nde5
18. a3 Bd6 19. Nac5 $14 {With active piece play around the isolated pawn.})
12... Qd8 13. N5d4 e5 14. Nxc6 bxc6 15. Rfd1 a5 16. cxd5 cxd5 17. Nc5 h6 18. a3
Bxc5 19. Bxc5 Re8 20. b4 Bb7 21. e3 $14 {Two bishops and an outside passed
pawn, combined with the pin along the long diagonal offers White pleasant play.
}) ({The best way to prepare ...Nc6 is} 6... a6 7. Bg2 Nc6 8. N2f3 (8. Nxc6
dxc6 {followed by ...e6-e5 does not offer White much, despite the engines'
initial optimism.}) 8... d6 ({Strongplayers refrain from} 8... Nxd4 9. Qxd4 Bc5
{although this seems to offer Black certain counterplay.} 10. Qd3 b5 11. cxb5
Qa5+ 12. Bd2 Qxb5 13. Qxb5 axb5 14. Nd4 Rb8 {Tsolakidou,S (2355)-Lahav,M (2054)
Khanty-Mansiysk 2016 (½-½, 37)} 15. Nb3 Bd6 16. Rc1 O-O 17. O-O {folowed by
Rfd1 with certain pressure.}) 9. O-O Bd7 10. b3 Be7 11. Bb2 O-O 12. Rc1 Rac8
13. Qd3 h6 14. Rfd1 Rfd8 15. e4 {This kind of positon is, of course, playable
with both sides, but it should not inhibit playing the Catalan, as White has
more space and active pieces.} e5 $5 16. Nc2 b5 {Fominyh,A (2475)-Khismatullin,
D (2649) Moscow 2011 (½-½, 57)} 17. Ne3 $14) (6... Bc5 7. N2b3 Be7 {wastes a
tempo for no obvious reasons.} 8. Qd3 a6 9. Bg2 d6 10. Bd2 $5 {Anticipating
Black's ...Nc6.} Bd7 (10... Nc6 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Ba5 Qd7 13. O-O O-O 14. Rfd1
Rb8 {This is the only regrouping allowing creating the threat ...c6-c5.} 15. c5
$5 d5 16. e4 $5 dxe4 17. Qe2 $14 Qb7 18. Bb6 $16 {with annoying domination.})
11. Ba5 Qc8 12. O-O O-O 13. Rac1 Nc6 14. Nxc6 Bxc6 15. e4 Qb8 16. Nd4 {with an
active Hedgehog for White, Huzman,A (2435)-Novikov,I (2480) Uzhgorod 1987 (1-0,
52)}) 7. Nb5 Qb8 (7... Qb6 8. Bg2 d5 9. O-O Be7 (9... d4 {Greanias, S (2125)
-Sarkar, J (2403) Cherry Hill 2007 (0-1, 54)} 10. Qa4 Bd7 11. c5 Bxc5 12. Nc4
Qd8 13. Nbd6+ Bxd6 14. Nxd6+ Kf8 15. Nxb7 Qb6 16. Qa3+ Kg8 17. Nc5 $16) (9...
dxc4 10. Qa4 a6 11. Nc3 Bd7 12. Nxc4 $16) {This has been played in a few games.
My suggestion is} 10. a4 $5 $146 a6 11. Nc3 d4 12. a5 Nxa5 (12... Qc7 13. Na4
O-O 14. Nb6 Rb8 15. Nb3 {offers White pleasant play.}) 13. Na4 Qd8 14. c5 Nc6
15. Nc4 $14 {The extra pawn is not too important and White is in complete
control. His main plan is based on e2-e3.}) 8. Bg2 a6 9. Nc3 b5 {Otherwise
Black risks landing in a passive position.} (9... Be7 10. Nde4 Nxe4 11. Nxe4 f5
12. Nc3 O-O 13. Bf4 d6 14. Qd2 Ne5 {Zontakh,A (2540)-Bocharov,D (2607) St
Petersburg 2009 (1-0, 35)} 15. c5 $14 dxc5 16. Nd5 $36) 10. O-O Be7 (10... bxc4
11. Nxc4 d5 12. Bf4 Qb4 13. Na4 $1 $16 {with better development and strong
initiative on the weakened dark squares.}) 11. Nde4 Nxe4 12. Nxe4 bxc4 13. Bf4
e5 14. Be3 {A familiar picture. Black has won a pawn but his development is
incomplete and he has many weaknesses.} O-O ({More natural than the rushed} 
14... f5 15. Nc3 f4 16. Bd2 O-O 17. e3 Nb4 18. a3 Nd3 {Szczepanski,Z (2494)
-Weeks,M (2192) LSS email 2013 (1-0, 72)} 19. b3 $16) 15. Nd2 Rd8 (15... Qxb2
16. Nxc4 Qb5 17. Nb6 $16) 16. Nxc4 (16. Bd5 $5) 16... d5 17. Qa4 $36 {With
strong initiative against Black's hanging position.} *

