[PlyCount "23"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 c5 4. Nf3 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Bb4+ {This is an open
invitation to the fianchetto Nimzoindian after 6.c3. This may be the most
principled answer but covering it hear would make no sense as this would
require a whole repertoire database. Maybe as a next project!?} 6. Bd2 Be7 {
This method is frequently seen in modern chess, in openings such as the
Queen's Indian, the Catalan and, of course, Bogo Indian. Apparently, Black has
lost a tempo, but White will have difficulties finding a good square for his
queen's bishop, which stands in the way of the own queen.} ({The early queen
development} 6... Qb6 {is as in many similar cases a bit risky.} 7. Bg2 Nc6 {
The safest continuation refraining from material gainings.} (7... Bc5 8. e3
Bxd4 (8... Qxb2 9. Nc3 $16 {leaves Black awfully underdeveloped.}) (8... Nc6 9.
Bc3 $14 d5 10. O-O Bxd4 $6 11. exd4 dxc4 12. d5 Nxd5 13. Bxg7 Rg8 14. Bc3 Nxc3
15. Nxc3 Bd7 16. Ne4 $16 {Karpov,A (2775)-Hracek,Z (2625) Cap d'Agde 1996 (1-0,
46)}) 9. exd4 Qxd4 10. Nc3 Qxc4 (10... O-O 11. Rc1 $1 $146 {+/=}) 11. Rc1 {
White has very strong initiative for the missing pawns.} Qd3 12. Nd5 Na6 13.
Nxf6+ gxf6 14. Rc3 Qb5 15. a4 Qxb2 16. O-O d5 17. Rd3 Qb6 18. Re1 Nc7 19. Qa1
Ke7 20. Rb1 $18 {Black will soon have no available squares for his king and
queen.}) (7... Qxd4 8. Bxb4 Qxb2 9. Bc3 Qb6 10. O-O O-O 11. Bxf6 gxf6 12. Nc3
Nc6 13. Ne4 Kg7 14. Rb1 Qc7 15. Qd2 Rd8 16. Nd6 $16 {Tukmakov,V (2566)-Adianto,
U (2572) Biel 2002 (½-½, 40)}) 8. Nb3 d5 (8... a5 9. O-O a4 10. Be3 Qa6 11.
Nc5 Qxc4 12. Nxa4 $14 {Birnboim,N (2395)-Veinger,I (2380) Rishon Le Ziyyon
1992 (1-0, 62)}) 9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. O-O O-O 11. Bxb4 Ndxb4 {Dorfman,J (2595)
-Ftacnik,L (2606) playchess.com INT 2006 (½-½, 39)} 12. N1d2 Rd8 13. a3 Nd5
14. Rc1 {White keeps some light pressure in a position which is typical for
the Catalan already.} a5 15. e3 a4 (15... Ne5 16. Rc2 $14) 16. Nd4 Nxd4 17. Nc4
Qa7 18. Qxd4 Qxd4 19. exd4 Ra6 20. Ne3 $14) ({In principle} 6... Bxd2+ 7. Qxd2
{helps White's development, but Black has} Ne4 8. Qc2 Qa5+ 9. Nd2 Nxd2 10. Qxd2
Qxd2+ 11. Kxd2 Nc6 12. Nb5 Ke7 13. Bg2 $14 {with just slightly more pleasant
for White.}) (6... Bc5 7. Nb3 Be7 {is similar to 5...Bc5 from the previous
line.} 8. Bg2 Nc6 9. O-O O-O 10. Nc3 d5 (10... d6 11. Bf4 a6 12. Rc1 $14) 11.
cxd5 exd5 12. Bg5 Be6 13. Rc1 $14) 7. Bg2 Nc6 8. Bf4 ({I prefer this active
move over} 8. Bc3 {which used to be the main line. The bishop's situation is
not that bad now, but usually, this is the best square for the knight, keeping
the d5-square under severe control.} O-O 9. O-O d5 {The logical consequence of
Black's previous play. With a white knight on c3, this move would leave Black
with a weak pawn on d5 after cxd5.} 10. Nd2 Qb6 11. e3 Bd7 12. a3 dxc4 13. Nxc4
Qa6 14. Qb3 {It is obvious now that the early development of Black's queen has
helped White win time for the coordination of his forces.} Nd5 15. Nxc6 Bxc6 {
In principle, Black has no problems, but by not finding a clear plan he will
land into a passive position.} 16. Bd4 Rfd8 17. Rfc1 Ba4 18. Qa2 b6 19. b3 Be8
20. Qb2 Bf8 21. e4 Ne7 22. a4 $14 {Jussupow,A (2645)-Gavrikov,V (2550)/Minsk
1987/URS-ch (1-0, 42). with domination for White.}) 8... O-O (8... Nxd4 $6 9.
Qxd4 {only activates White's pieces.} d6 10. Qd2 Qc7 11. Nc3 Bd7 12. Rc1 $16 {
Miton,K (2601)-Krejci,J (2533) Germany 2014 (1-0, 76)}) 9. Nc3 {The reason why
White should prefer this over castling is revealed below.} e5 {A unsuccessful
attempt at freeing Black's position. But other moves also offer White active
play.} (9... a6 10. O-O Nxd4 11. Qxd4 d6 12. Qd3 Qc7 13. Rfd1 Rd8 14. Rac1 Nh5
(14... Rb8 15. c5 $18) 15. Be3 ({More active than} 15. Bd2 {which is also OK.}
Rb8 16. Ne4 Nf6 17. Nxf6+ Bxf6 18. Bf4 $14 {Topalov,V (2690)-Kramnik,V (2760)
Las Vegas 1999 (0-1, 40)}) 15... Bd7 (15... Nf6 16. Na4 $14) 16. Bd4 Rac8 (
16... Be8 {simply loses a pawn:} 17. Qf3 Nf6 18. Qxb7 Qxb7 19. Bxb7 Rab8 20.
Bxa6 Rxb2 21. a4 $16 {Watson,J (2420)-Slaton,D Pasadena 1983 (1-0, 39)}) 17.
Qe3 Re8 18. Ne4 Bc6 19. Bf3 d5 20. cxd5 exd5 21. Nc3 $16) (9... d5 {plays into
White's hands as he has a harmonious development.} 10. O-O Qb6 $5 11. Be3 Qxb2
12. cxd5 exd5 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. Bxd5 Bh3 {Hutters,T (2445)-Romanishin,O (2595)
Tastrup 1992 (½-½, 19)} 15. Rb1 Qa3 16. Rxb7 Nxd4 17. Qxd4 Bxf1 18. Kxf1 $14
{White will soon have two pawns for the exchange and an active position.}) (
9... Qb6 10. Nb3 a5 {can be met with} 11. Na4 $14 {which justifies the early
knight's development.}) 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Bxe5 Qa5 12. Bd6 $14 {Even if White
will lose his extra pawn, strategically his position remains preferable,
Dominguez Perez,L (2713)-Gashimov,V (2740) Nice 2010 (0-1, 48).} *

