1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 c5 4. Nf3 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 {Black plays in the spirit
of one of the main Symmetrical English systems.} 6. Bg2 $1 {The best way to
restrict Black's counterplay.} (6. Nc3 Qb6 {would transpose to the
aforementioned system. Despite some occasional wins in the past, I came to the
conclusion that proving an advantage with white is very hard.}) {Black can try
many continuations, most of them bearing similarity with the main English line
with Nc3 instead of Bg2, but White seems to be prepared against all of them.}
6... Bc5 ({If} 6... Bb4+ {White can transpose back to the main lines, as in
those 6...Bb4 is not the very best.} 7. Nc3 O-O 8. O-O Qe7 (8... a6 9. Bf4 $14)
9. Na4 $5 ({The tempting} 9. Nc2 {gains the two bishops at the cost of losing
time and removing the knight from its central position.} Bxc3 10. bxc3 Rd8 11.
Ba3 d6 12. Rb1 Qc7 13. Nd4 Nxd4 14. cxd4 Qxc4 15. Qd2 Qa6 16. Rb3 $44 {Kramnik,
V (2710)-Kamsky,G (2695) New York 1994 (0-1, 38) with just reasonable
compensation.}) 9... d5 {Black needs reacting in the centre as otherwise his
bishop would stay completely misplaced.} 10. cxd5 exd5 (10... Nxd5 11. Nxc6
bxc6 {½-½ Neverov,V (2530)-Obukhov,A (2415) Perm 1997} 12. Qc2 Ba6 13. a3 Bd6
14. Re1 $14 Rfc8 15. e4 Nb6 16. e5 Bc7 17. Bd2 Nxa4 18. Qxa4 Bb5 19. Qg4 $14)
11. Be3 {hite has obtained a comfortable version of the Tarrasch Defence.} Bg4
12. a3 Bd6 13. Re1 Rfd8 14. Rc1 Rac8 15. Nxc6 bxc6 16. Bc5 h5 17. Qd4 $14 {
Adianto,U (2585)-Bezold,M (2495) New York 1995 (0-1, 61)}) (6... Qb6 {offers
Black less counterplay as after 6.Nc3 as the c4-pawn is less vulnerable.} 7.
Nb5 Ne5 {This is the main resource for counterplay in the similar system with
6.Nc3, but here White can maintain his space advantage intact with} (7... d5 8.
O-O $1 (8. Be3 d4 9. Nxd4 Ng4 $44) 8... dxc4 9. N1c3 Bc5 10. Nd6+ Bxd6 11. Qxd6
$14 {as played in several games.}) (7... Bb4+ 8. N1c3 {Once again the early
bishop's commitment justifies returning to the main paths.} a6 9. Nd6+ Ke7 10.
Nxc8+ Raxc8 11. O-O Bxc3 12. bxc3 Na5 13. Rb1 Qc7 14. Qa4 b6 15. c5 bxc5 {
Nikolic,P (2584)-Almasi,Z (2640) Germany 2006 (½-½, 49)} 16. Bf4 d6 17. Rfd1
Rhd8 18. c4 $16 {Despite his extra pawn Black is almost completely paralyzed.})
8. Be3 Bc5 9. Bxc5 Qxc5 10. N1a3 $14 {as played in a few games.}) (6... a6 {
spoils the variation's spirit by delaying the counterattack.} 7. O-O Qc7 8. Nc3
Be7 9. b3 O-O 10. Bb2 d6 11. Rc1 Nxd4 (11... Bd7 12. Nd5 $1) 12. Qxd4 Bd7 13.
Rfd1 Rfd8 (13... Rac8 14. Ne4 Ne8 15. Ba3 {wins a pawn.}) 14. b4 $1 Rac8 15. b5
$36 {Romero Holmes,A (2473)-Campora,D (2526) Elgoibar 2000 (1-0, 30)}) 7. Nb3
Bb4+ ({The passive} 7... Be7 {offers White free hands to consolidate his space
advantage.} 8. Nc3 O-O 9. O-O d6 10. Bf4 Nh5 11. e3 $5 {More or less forcing
Black to strengthen White's domination in the center and clear the e-file for
his king's rook. The following game is very instructive about how to use the
accumulation of positional factors for a tactical explosion:} Nxf4 12. exf4 Bd7
13. Qd2 Qb8 14. Rfe1 g6 15. h4 a6 16. h5 b5 17. hxg6 hxg6 18. Nc5 dxc5 19. Qxd7
Rc8 20. Rxe6 Ra7 21. Rxg6+ fxg6 22. Qe6+ Kg7 23. Bxc6 $16 {Karpov,A (2740)
-Topalov,V (2640) Linares 1994 (1-0, 39)}) 8. Nc3 {A familiar issue. We are
back in a slightly inferior for Black variation of the main system.} d5 9. cxd5
Nxd5 10. O-O $1 {We are already used with this kind of sacrifices for
initiative and development.} Nxc3 (10... Bxc3 11. bxc3 O-O (11... Nxc3 12. Qc2
Nd5 13. Ba3 $16) 12. Ba3 Re8 13. c4 Nb6 14. Rc1 $16 {Adorjan,A (2515)
-Sigurjonsson,G (2435) Reykjavik 1982 (1-0, 38)}) 11. Qxd8+ Kxd8 (11... Nxd8
12. bxc3 Bxc3 13. Rb1 a5 (13... Bb4 14. Nd4 a5 15. Nb5 O-O 16. Nc7 Rb8 17. a3
Be7 18. Bf4 g5 19. Be5 f6 20. Nd5 $14) 14. a3 $5 $146 {Preventing the bishop's
return to the a3-f8 diagonal.} O-O 15. Rd1 $36) 12. bxc3 Bxc3 13. Rb1 a5 14.
Be3 Bb4 {The fine thing in these positions is that White can count on
retrieving the pawn (for instance on b7) the only open question remaining
whether this would offer him a clear or just a symbolic advantage.} 15. Rfc1 (
15. Nc5 Ke7 {Kasparov,G (2700)-Wegner,H (2210) Hamburg (simul) 1985 (½-½, 33)
} 16. Na4) 15... Ke7 16. Nd4 Bd7 17. Nb5 Kf6 18. a3 Be7 19. h4 Kg6 20. Rd1 $16
{With overwhelming activity in Lautier, J (2645)-Leko, P (2555) Cap d'Agde
1994 (1-0, 27)} *

